    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Thin, pale yellowish-brown, cushion-like alga, attached by a broad base. Comprised of a thin, smooth, convoluted surface skin comprising only a few layers of cells and enclosing a large internal cavity.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6791",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Total length can reach 10 cm, but more typically 2-4 cm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6792",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in tropical and temperate seas around the world.</p><p><u>Local/Regional</u><i><u>:</u> </i>Namibia to Mozambique.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6793",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically found attached to other algae, on intertidal rocks, or in pools. During the day oxygen generated by photosynthesis may accumulate in the internal cavity and the ball may become buoyant, lifting not only the alga itself but anything it is attached to – hence the common name oyster thief!&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6794",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6795",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Tiny sporangia embedded in surface and often in clusters around hair bundles.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6796",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Often confused with Brown brains <i>Leathesia marina,</i> but that species is darker in colour and has thicker walls and a smaller internal cavity.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6797",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
